text: President Trump can, in fact, pardon himself from the GA charges if he is elected president. 1. The Constitution's silent about whether a president can be indicted. 2. The DOJ has taken the position under both parties that you cannot indict a sitting president because it would cripple the executive branch and make his ability to defend himself effectively impossible. 3. Given the DOJ's position, and the Supremacy Clause in the Constitution, I would argue strongly that the idea that a president cannot be indicted at the federal level because it would cripple the executive branch, but can be indicted by local DAs, would have exactly the same effect as a federal indictment, except there are thousands of local and state prosecutors making the crippling of a president even more likely. 4. FURTHERMORE, if indicted and even convicted, the idea that a president cannot pardon himself from state charges is absurd, again, not only because of the Supremacy Clause, but the same considerations that apply to a federal conviction would obviously apply to a state conviction. text: Respectfully, Jonathan Turley is simply wrong. The Constitution is silent on whether you can indict a sitting president or whether a president can pardon himself, even for federal offenses. I challenge Jonathan to demonstrate otherwise. Moreover, the argument that a president cannot be indicted is based on practicality and rationality, nothing more and nothing less. That is the position of the Justice Department under attorneys' general of both parties -- first in a 1973 memorandum by the Office of Legal Counsel (under the Nixon administration), and subsequently endorsed by a second memorandum by OLC in 2000 (under the Clinton administration). The position taken is that you cannot have the executive branch decapitated or crippled by a president who is having to spend an enormous amount of time defending his freedom; that we cannot have an elected president who is convicted running the executive branch from prison; and, of course, the impact on foreign policy and national security could be disastrous. The idea, as Jonathan seems to argue, without any constitutional bases (his reference to federalism in this context is utterly irrelevant), does not address the problems raised by the DOJ decades ago. This has nothing to do with the general pardon power where a president does not reach into state affairs and pardon individuals for charges and convictions based on state law violations. This involves a sitting president, elected by the voters to serve as president, who serves at the top of the executive branch. The rational argument must be that local and state prosecutors have no more ability to decapitate or cripple the federal executive branch and a president than do federal prosecutors, under the argument set forth by DOJ. Although they don't address state charges, the reasons a president can pardon himself when faced with federal indictments are exactly the same when it comes to state charges. And it is those reasons that the DOJ has taken the position is has. In fact, since there are literally thousands of local and state prosecutors, the argument is even more compelling when applied to non-federal prosecutors. Can one imagine the mayhem that would result from local or state prosecutors free to act as Jonathan suggests they can? This is among the reasons why the actions in NY and Georgia by local Democrat DAs are so disastrous to the nation, apart from the abuse of grand juries and the law. There is nothing novel about what I am saying, any more than it is novel to argue that a president can pardon himself from federal indictments. As I said, the Constitution does not address the indictment or pardon issue in that context. Nonetheless, I take into account what the official DOJ position has been for over half a century respecting the impact an indictment would have on the ability of a president to defend himself and run the country. I agree with that view. But it is not based on some hidden language in the Constitution. It is based on practical consequences. Jonathan's view is not based on the Constitution. text: It's not particularly useful when NeverTrumpers from the time Trump announced his run for president in 2015 are making declarations to Trump supporters and the GOP base today insisting that they abandon their man for, well, I guess, anyone else since, in this case, Andy McCarthy doesn't tell us. Respectfully, such a declaration is mostly self-serving. The fact is that the Democrat Party and NeverTrumpers have done some of the most unthinkable things to cripple the Trump presidency and post-presidency in ways that will permanently damage our republic. Of course, they tell us, that's mostly Trump's fault. He brought it on himself. Since the guy was treated like dirt even before he was elected, that criticism is hard to stomach. And he was elected by many to take a sledgehammer to the DC ruling class -- that is, to do what others have promised but never accomplished. But this is not a post about all that. McCarthy may well be right, but there are candidates running for the GOP nomination who are not named Trump who couldn't get elected dog catcher in their own states, most of whom are establishment Republicans who have no clue how to address what has been and is being done to our country -- namely, a literal revolution by one party against the other party and the country -- and were weak and largely ineffective in their prior political positions. And several could get clobbered in a general election for many reasons, including if they cannot attract the vote of MAGA voters and other conservatives. The numbers simply won't add up. The likes of Larry Hogan, Asa Hutchison, Lisa Murkowski, and Chris Christie (in his own way) have every intention of abandoning the GOP should Trump be nominated. (Bill Barr is prepared to jump off a bridge, which could be fatal given his likely lack of buoyancy.) That said, conservatives of all types, not just MAGA supporters, are rightly fed up with the likes of Mitch McConnell, the longest serving Senate leader ever, who doesn't lift a finger to elect conservatives like Cruz, Lee, Johnson, et al, but spends millions from his special interest funded PAC to elect Murkowski, Collins, et al. This defines the entire GOP Senate leadership. McConnell has done nothing to help expose the Biden family corruption and publicly tells the House GOP (which cannot stand him) not to open an impeachment inquiry, while giving a long interview to Politico about how he is sabotaging Trump. But he is fiercely defended by the DC Republicans and their media and think-tank surrogates for doing a handful of things, especially related to judges, that any Senate GOP leader (especially a conservative) would have done. They've had enough of the lingering political operatives, like Karl Rove and others, who couldn't even back Ronald Reagan in 1976 and in the 1980 GOP primary (incidentally, McConnell backed Ford over Reagan in 1976, as did my friend Hugh Hewitt). Chris Christie is the most despised of all GOP candidates by all Republicans. He receives a tremendous amount of free media on all news platforms, despite the fact he cannot win a general election without significant Republican support. In my view, he would lose a general election in a landslide. And I could go down the list. I could also go on about this general subject, and no doubt will have to given what will be the utterly predictable responses from the usual GOP voices and establishment-backing commentariat. That said, McCarthy is a very good legal analyst, with whom I sometimes disagree, but the rest of this is the usual stuff. And if Trump gets the nomination and loses the general, he and others can pat themselves on the back and say "I told you so." But they've told us nothing. Perhaps any GOP nominee would lose or would win; hard to tell right now. It is not "very simple." And the "I told you so" crowd never remind us when they've told us when they've been dead wrong. Nobody really gives a damn anyway. By the way, my unsolicited advice: YOU are running for and want to be president. YOU think you are the best suited to be president. PROVE IT! The media will have its own agenda -- Trump, abortion, Biden impeachment, etc. Be prepared for it. Someone like Christie is there to attack and bully. Be ready to dismiss him. Others are slick talkers. Politely pin them down -- blank slates make for poor presidents. Show some charisma, have a personality, address the American people and try to connect with what they are experiencing, point to your accomplishments, and most of all, IMHO, demonstrate that you know the nation is unraveling and you intend to do serious things about it. FWIW.
